{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949041501/1148.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME NUGGET\nPublished Monday, Wednesday and Friday by the\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNOME, ALASKA\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 61 a\n$1.50 PER MONTH $16.00 A YEAR\nW. A. Boucher .Owner-Publisher\nEntered as second class matter October 14, 1943. at the postoffice\nat Nome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNome, Alaska, Friday, April 15, 1949\nA CONGRESSMEN S DECISION\n(Bv Clarke Beach, (/P) Features Writer)\nWhat do Congressmen think about when they cast\ntheir votes in the House of Representatives?\nMany of them have thinking apparatuses with a kind\nof high and low gear. This was clearly demonstrated\nwhen two votes were taken on a motion to kill the vet\nerans\u2019 pension bill. On the first vote the majority of\nCongressmen decided to kill the bill. On the second\nvote, taken within an hour, the majority decided not to\nkill it.\nOn the first vote the House was sitting as a \u201ccommit\ntee of the whole\u201d when an individual\u2019s vote is not re\ncorded. On the second test the body was sitting as the\nHouse of Representatives, and a record was kept of how\neach member voted.\nWhen the vote was taken in committee status, lbd\nmembers voted to kill the measure. When they voted in\nHouse status, only 120 voted to kill. Thus at least 43\nCongressmen either switched sides or failed to vote\nwhen the roll was called.\n\u201cI voted on principle when my vote wasn\u2019t on the rec\nord,\" one well-known legislator jovially explained.\n\u201cWhen I was on the record, I rose above principle and\nvoted politically.\u201d Another member, one of the 120 who\nstuck by his original vote, got a good natured slap on\nthe back from a colleague after the balloting was over.\n\u201cWell, guess we won't be seing you around here any\nmore after next year,\u201d said the colleague. \u201cIt's great to\nbe a statesman. But I\u2019d rather be a live Congressman\nthan a dead statesman.'\u2019\nRep. Javits (R.-N. Y.) said on the floor that he had\nmade up his mind after a sleepless night to vote against\nthe pension measure. \u201cIf we are taken in by this, we do\nnot deserve to be trusted with the destiny of America,\nmuch less that of the world,\u201d he remarked.\nOne Congressman told this reporter that on every roll\ncall vote some member or other risks his political future\nby voting in a way that he knows will be unpopular\namong his constituents. The folks back home probably\nwon't read the Congressional record, and many of them\nwill not know at the time how he voted. But there is al\nways someone back home waiting for him to make a\nslip. That someone undoubtedly will use the record\nagainst him when campaign time comes.\nIf he is licked, he won\u2019t be in the House to vote the:\nright way when some other measure comes up which\nmay be more important. Thus runs the philosophy of\nmany members, says one seasoned Representative.\nMany say that eventually they want to do something\ngood for their country but that if they don\u2019t stay in Con\ngress they\u2019ll never be able to do it.\nThe issues which can be poisonous generally concern\nthe constituent\u2019s pocketbooks, one Congressman mused.\nTheir pensions, taxes, agricultural and other subsidies,\nthe building of public works, the extension of govern\nment controls over business.\nSome of the poisonous issues, he went on, carry their\nown antidotes. If you cast a vote for oleomargarine, you\nantagonize the dairymen but you gain the support of\nthe housewives. If you cast a vote that angers lafoor you\ngain the support of management. If you back rent con\ntrol you make landlords your enemy but gain friends\namong tenants.\n\u201cBut when you cast a vote that seems to be against\nveterans,\u201d he continued, \u201cthere\u2019s nobody to save you.\nNobody is opposed the veterans. Least of all me.\u201d (He is\na veteran himself).\nAnother war veteran, who is a freshman in the House,\nthus analyzed the frame of mind of many of his col\nleagues:\n\u201cTheir voting for pensions isn\u2019t so much a matter of\nshrewd political analysis. They are being controlled by\nWe lift our hearts exultingly to ccclaim the Cross.\nGrant all of us the power of the resurrection is our\nearnest prayer this Easter Season.\ntheir fears. They don't know how good a case there is\nagainst taking up veterans' pensions at this time with\nout thorough committee spade-work on the thing.\n\u201cI think if the leadership of the House had taken a\nstronger position and had come up with good strong ar\nguments, their courage could have been bolstered. I\ndon't think I\u2019ve killed myself politically by opposing the\nbill. I believe the people of my district will approve of\nwhat I\u2019ve done when they hear what I have to say about\n'a.\nIt.\nEXPERTS WOULD FORTIFY THE MOON\nWith few explanations, said to be omitted for secur\nity reasons, the House recently unanimously approved\nthe establishment of a $161,000,000 network of land\nbased radar warning and control installations at points\nthroughout the country believed by the military to be\nthe most effective against sudden and secret enemy at\ntack.\nIn addition, at an estimated government cost of $200.\n000,000, the House approved the building up of a prov\ning ground, 3.000 miles in range, for trying out guided\nmissiles. It was stated that the present try-out installa\ntions were being fast outgrown.\nIt is difficult for the people of the United States to\npass intelligent judgment upon the necessity for such\nexpenditures but, in the absence of general information,\none must presume that the military leaders of the na\ntion are acting intelligently in asserting that there is\nimmediate need to get these plans started.\nIt was pointed out by one member of the House that\nan enemy, having aircraft comparable to our B-36,\nwould be able to escape interception by flying at 40,000\nfeet at a speed of about seven miles a minute. A radar\nwarning of their approach, he insisted, would have to\nbe given while the airplanes were at least 185 miles\naway for effective interception.\nWhile we are cognizant of the tendency of military\nexperts to exaggerate the potential of our possible en\nemies and of the fact that they would \u201cfortify the moon\u201d\nif they could get the funds and reach the earth\u2019s satel\nlite, we find it difficult to believe that responsible ad\n1 visers of Congress, on matters of defense, are so intense\n1 ly interested in their particular branches of the armed\nforces that they would ash for such expenditures with\nout reasonable evidence that they are necessary in the\ndefense of the United States.\n_:_\nIt seems impossible to determine whether the nation\nj is in the beginning of a recession of just catching its\nbreath for another round of inflation The Russians\nprofess to believe that the whole world is plotting\nI against the Soviet; they will be dangerous, perhaps, if\nthe time comes that they really believe it. The peo\npie of Nome would be surprised at what they could oc\ncomplish when they just make up their minds to accom\nplish something.\nCHURCHES\nCATHOLIC CHURCH\nLenten Devotions\nTonight\u20147:30\nServices in honor of the Passion\nof our Lord.\nHoly Saturday\u2014\nBlessing of Easter Water and\nEaster Candle\u20145:30 a.m.\nMass\u20146:30 a.m.\nEaster Sunday\u20148:00\nMass and First Communion ex\nercises.\n9:30\u2014High Mass.\nThere will be no mass at the\nBase Chapel.\nLAVINIA WALLACE YOUNG\nMISSION\nPastors Rev. H. R. Amundsen\nand Rev. Theran McGrew\nSunday:\n11:00 a.m. Sunday School.\n7.30 p.m. Evening Service.\nWednesday 3:30 p rn C v.'.\ndren\u2019s M.racle Book Club.\nThursday 7:30 p.m. Prayer\nMeeting.\nFEDERATED CHURCH\nSunday, 10:00 a.m. Sunday School\nEaster Program, followed by egg\nhunt for the children and coffee\nfor the parents.\nSuperintendent,. Mrs. Ken Rank\nEvening Services 8:00 p.m.\nSpeaker, Chaplain R. W. Fricke.\nCommunity chorus directed by\nMrs. W. Cameron.\nPENTACOSTAL ASSEMBLY OF\nGOD\nThird Avenue West\n\nSunday\u2014\nSunday School 10:00 a.m.\nSpecial Easter Service 11:00 a.m.\nEvening Service 7:30 p.m.\nTuesday\u2014\nYoung Peoples Meeting 4:00 p.m.\nWednesday\u2014\nBible Study 7:30 p.m.\nFriday\u2014\nBible Study and\nPrayer Meeting 7:00 p.m.\nEVERYONE WELCOME\nCHURCH CF THE NAZARENE\nThird and Division\nPaster\u2014Lewis I. Hudgins\n\u201cGreater love hath no man than\nthis, that a man lay down his life\nfor his friends.\u2019\u2019 John 15.13.\n10:00 a m. Singspiraiion and Sun\nday School classes.\n11:00 a.m. Morning message.\n7:00 p.m. Young People\u2019s Meeting.\n7:30 p.m. Singspiration and special\nmusic.\n8:00 p.m. Evening message.\nWednesday: 7:30 p.m. Melody an\nPrayer.\nCome and bring your Bible.\nYou are ever welcome t\u00a9 attend\nthese services.\nNOME GOSPEL MISSION\nof\nAlaska Evangelisation Society\nRev. Yarn Rivaling. Patter\n4\nSunday:\n2:00 p.m. Sunday School far\nboys and girls.\nPreaching service in the Eskimo\nlanguage by James Savok.\n7:30 p.m. Gospel Servioe.\nTuesday:\n7:30 p.m. Prayer and Testimony\nj Thursday:\n2:00 to 4:00 p.m. Bible Club for\ni Boys and Girls.\nFriday:\n7:30 p.m. Bible Study.\nPAA OFFICE TO BE CLOSED\nSATURDAY AFTERNOON\nThe Pan American office will\nbe closed Saturday afternoon on\naccount of the Easter services. In\ncase of emergency call Black 70.","height":"27296","width":"19644"}}
